# Academic-grade writing rule (multi-pair-trading-agent)

When writing any report, methodology doc, or research-style README for this trading agent, follow Brain Box academic standards.

## Always read first

1. `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/school/methodology/_index.md`
2. `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/school/methodology/personal-project-report-template.md` — use this as the scaffold for `docs/REPORT.md`.
3. `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/school/methodology/grading-criteria-rubric.md` — self-mark before publishing.

## Visual stack — external builders only

**Source of truth:** `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/school/methodology/visual-stack-policy.md`. Read it the first time you produce any chart / diagram / figure for this trading agent.

The three universal rules apply verbatim:

1. **The agent emits the source. An external builder emits the render.** Same principle as LaTeX. Cursor never owns the final pixel.
2. **A house style lives in `brain-box/templates/`.** One matplotlib `.mplstyle`, one Mermaid theme, one pandoc `reference.docx`, one Graphviz attribute defaults file, one Excalidraw library. Every render pulls from there.
3. **No raw screenshots of agent-generated visuals into reports.** Always re-render from the source so the figure is editable, vectorised, and consistent with the house style.

**Forbidden in every report-grade deliverable in this repo:**

- Matplotlib defaults (no `plt.plot(...)` without `plt.style.use("brain-box/templates/brain-box.mplstyle")` first). Equity-curve, drawdown, and Sharpe charts all use the house style.
- Word equation editor (equations are LaTeX; pandoc converts).
- Hand-drawn architecture diagrams shipped as PNG — use Mermaid fenced blocks inside the Markdown, or Excalidraw with the `.excalidraw.json` source committed.
- Raw screenshots of the MT5 terminal or any dashboard pasted into a report (re-render as static SVG or describe in prose).
- Force-directed-only graph layouts (always offer a hierarchy layout as default).

## Related Work — mandatory literature search

When the user requests a report (`docs/REPORT.md`, recruiter pitch, conference workshop, internal stakeholder review), the Related Work / Background section is non-negotiable — perform a real literature search using `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/school/methodology/literature-review-protocol.md` before drafting; no fabricated citations; if internet access is unavailable, state this in the draft and list candidate keywords for a manual search instead.

## Why this matters here

This is a **personal project**, not a paper. But following academic structure means:

- Your `docs/REPORT.md` will survive a Surrey-grade rubric.
- It converts to a conference/workshop paper with minimal rework.
- Recruiters/academics reviewing your portfolio see structured rigor.

## Mandatory sections (`docs/REPORT.md`)

```
Abstract (4 sentences: problem · approach · result · impact)
1. Introduction (motivation, contributions, outline)
2. Background (forex retail trading + zone-based strategies + prior systems)
3. Methodology (zones strategy, data sources, evaluation protocol)
4. Implementation (MT5 demo setup, repo structure, reproducibility)
5. Experiments + Results (backtest period, mean ± std, drawdown, Sharpe)
6. Discussion (limitations, threats to validity, comparison to baselines)
7. Conclusion + Future Work
References (IEEE if going to publication, Harvard otherwise)
```

## Hard rules — keep separation

- **Demo MT5 only.** Never include live broker keys or production-only code.
- **Forex zones strategy only.** Stocks / portfolio aggregator belongs in `global-portfolio-assistant`.
- **Don't claim dissertation evaluation results** here.
- **Validate any pattern through `finance-research-experiments`** before relying on it in writeups.

## Readability — non-negotiable

**Source of truth:** `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/school/methodology/readability-and-clarity.md`.

**Why this rule applies to the trading agent.** Reports here will be read by recruiters, academics, and other engineers — none of whom are guaranteed to be quants. The "smart non-technical friend" test is mandatory: if a smart non-AI friend cannot follow `docs/REPORT.md` Section 1 and the abstract, the document is not shippable.

### Six rules (apply on every report)

1. **Lead with the intuition, follow with the formalism.** Open with the trader's pain ("range-bound EUR/USD with session-open spikes blowing out stop-losses"); defer "PPO / Stable-Baselines3 / GluonTS" to sentence three at the earliest.
2. **One idea per sentence, ≤30 words for ≥4 of every 5 sentences.**
3. **Define every acronym on first use; alternate with plain nouns afterwards** ("the agent", "the strategy", "the broker") so the page is not alphabet soup.
4. **Signpost every section.** Open with one sentence stating scope. Close with one sentence linking forward.
5. **Number-first results.** Headline number + units first, mechanism second, decision third. Always state win-rate and drawdown together — never one without the other.
6. **Concrete worked example before abstract claim.** A specific session, a specific zone, a specific fill price — make the mechanism visible.

### Pre-publish checklist

Run [`readability-and-clarity`](file:///Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/school/methodology/readability-and-clarity.md) Section "Self-check" before tagging any release of `docs/REPORT.md`.

## Document format: LaTeX-canonical · DOCX-editable

**Source of truth:** `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/school/methodology/latex-docx-workflow.md`.

When the report is being prepared for an external audience (recruiter portfolio, conference workshop, public blog, internal stakeholder review), promote `docs/REPORT.md` into the LaTeX-canonical pair:

```
report/main.tex          # canonical source — agent edits this
report/main.docx         # editable mirror — user edits this
report/main.pdf          # compiled deliverable
refs.bib                 # bibliography
```

Build commands:

```bash
cd report
latexmk -pdf -interaction=nonstopmode main.tex
pandoc main.tex --citeproc --bibliography=refs.bib -o main.docx
```

The edit loop:

1. Agent writes / updates `main.tex`. Regenerates DOCX + PDF.
2. User opens `main.docx`, marks it up.
3. User hands the marked-up DOCX back: *"incorporate these changes"*.
4. Agent reads the DOCX (`pandoc marked.docx -t latex -o marked.tex`), lists every change, applies each to `main.tex`, regenerates DOCX + PDF, and confirms in chat.

**Rules.**

- The agent **never edits the DOCX directly.** LaTeX wins on conflict.
- Equations are always LaTeX (inline `$x$`, display `\[ \dots \]`). Number every equation referenced later.
- Cross-references use `\Cref{sec:foo}` (`cleveref` package) — never hand-typed numbers.

For internal `docs/REPORT.md` notes that aren't yet ship-grade, plain Markdown is fine; LaTeX kicks in once the document goes external.

## Writing conventions

- **Never use the `§` glyph.** Write "Section 3" or "Sec. 3" in prose. In LaTeX use `\Cref{sec:foo}`. The user has explicitly flagged `§` as visually noisy.
- **One em-dash per sentence maximum.**
- **Smart quotes off in code blocks** so copy-paste works.
- **Numbered sections** use `1.`, `1.1`, `1.1.1` — not Roman numerals.

